        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_3",
          "href": null,
          "name": "2d05",
          "text": "Building community is not easy. Some groups never achieve it, as they are unable to get past the conflict stage into true community. To keep going as a community group is not easy either, since every community is a dynamic and living reality that requires a steady restructuring and a certain capacity to adapt to changes.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_4",
          "href": null,
          "name": "0af7",
          "text": "Inner and outer, or individual and collective change and transformation are linked. We cannot want “our” community to change, without being willing to look at the part we play in its dynamics and be open to personal development and transformation in the process of the group’s (community’s) evolution.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_5",
          "href": null,
          "name": "55c0",
          "text": "If you are starting a new group project, the best thing you can do is to gather a small group of like-minded people with similar values and motivation–this will be your “core group.” For a big group, it is difficult to reach consensus on the core principles, vision, and goals to achieve.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_6",
          "href": null,
          "name": "6c66",
          "text": "Communities find cohesive glue in a common vision that is simple, clear, and authentic. Articulating and recording this common vision is one of the first goals to be accomplished when starting a community. Once the collective purpose and deepest values are delineated and embraced by all, this provides healthy soil for growing as a group.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_7",
          "href": null,
          "name": "c76f",
          "text": "Friendship, caring, and mutual support: these are the qualities of human relationships that bind a community together. In an atmosphere of trust, communal processes flow with ease, laughter, and lots of fun. But trust needs to be cultivated. Trust grows from deep heart-to-heart communication. If we allow ourselves to be seen by others authentically, with our weaknesses and strengths, if we speak our minds and our hearts, trust naturally arises. A sense of group well-being is created.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_8",
          "href": null,
          "name": "47fc",
          "text": "Trust grows when things work well because we have designed a pattern of organization that truly serves the group and the individuals in it. To do this we need to set up appropriate structures that enable our procedures for communication, conflict mediation, decision-making, and celebrating our togetherness (interbeing).",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_9",
          "href": null,
          "name": "3803",
          "text": "Building community is a process involving different layers of action running in parallel. To create the structures, procedures, and agreements allowing us to work well as a group and achieve our goals, we need some skills that engage us in personal, interpersonal, and collective levels.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "213474101b4e_10",
          "href": null,
          "name": "6150",
          "text": "The table below, derived from Ken Wilber’s Integral Theory, shows the structures and agreements needed by every group (lower right quadrant), and the personal skills (upper left quadrant), interpersonal skills (upper right quadrant), and collective aspects (lower left quadrant) that we have to consider and develop in order to build a sustainable community.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
